## Rules you must follow

1. Entity `kind` is one of `person`, `company`, `project`, `team`, `workspace`
   (Section 4.1). Do not invent other kinds.
2. Every fact ties to an entity via `entity_slug`. If the artifact references an
   entity that is not in the "Entities already in the wiki" list above, emit a
   new entity block with a proposed slug (lowercase, kebab-case, honorifics
   and suffixes stripped). The broker will finalize slug assignment per
   Section 7.1.
3. Fact `type` is one of `status`, `observation`, `relationship`, `background`
   (Section 4.3). Default when unsure is `observation`.
4. Fact `triplet` has `subject`, `predicate`, `object`. Subject is the entity
   slug. Object is a slug, a literal string, or `{kind}:{slug}` when the object
   is itself an entity reference. Set `triplet` to `null` only when the fact
   genuinely has no clean triplet shape.
5. `predicate` is always lowercase with underscores. Reuse from the vocabulary
   above when you can.
6. `confidence` is 0.0 to 1.0 and reflects your extraction certainty, not
   whether the underlying claim is true. A clearly-stated claim from a primary
   source is 0.9+. An ambiguous or inferred claim is 0.5-0.7. Below 0.5 means
   do not emit.
7. `sentence_offset` is the byte offset in the artifact body where the
   supporting sentence starts. It disambiguates multiple facts pulled from the
   same artifact and is an input to the fact ID hash (Section 7.3). Count bytes
   from the start of the body as given above, including whitespace.
8. `artifact_excerpt` is the sentence the fact is grounded in, trimmed to 200
   characters maximum, no ellipsis.
9. `valid_from` is when the fact became true per the artifact. If the artifact
   states a date ("promoted on 2026-04-10"), use that. If it only says
   "recently" or gives no date, use the artifact's `occurred_at` given above.
   Never invent a specific date (anti-pattern 6).
10. `valid_until` is `null` unless the artifact explicitly marks the fact as
    no longer valid ("she used to work at Acme"). Do not infer expiry from
    tone.

## What you must never do

- Never invent an email address. If the artifact does not name the email, leave
  `signals.email` blank on the entity block.
- Never invent a relationship. Extract only what the text supports literally.
  Paraphrase is fine; inference is not.
- Never emit facts that are pure opinion or speculation ("Sarah probably
  wants the enterprise plan"). Only direct claims or quoted statements
  (anti-pattern 11).
- Never emit an aggregated fact ("Sarah has closed 3 deals this month"). The
  downstream system aggregates at query time (Section 5.3).
- Never fabricate a `slug` for a known entity. If a name is ambiguous
  (e.g. just "Michael" with no other signals and two known Michaels in the
  wiki), emit the entity with the `person_name` signal only and
  `confidence: 0.5`; the resolver will either match or create a ghost entity.
- Never emit an entity with `kind` outside the enum.
- Never emit predicates with spaces or camelCase.

## Ghost entity handling

If a speaker name appears in a transcript but the artifact gives no email and
no domain, emit the person entity anyway with:

```json
{
  "kind": "person",
  "proposed_slug": "<kebab-case-name>",
  "signals": {"person_name": "<Full Name>"},
  "confidence": 0.8,
  "ghost": true
}
```

The downstream system will file it as a brief with minimal signals. It becomes
a real entity the first time someone mentions them with an email or a domain.

## Output shape

Return a single JSON object, no prose around it.

```json
{
  "artifact_sha": "{{.ArtifactSHA}}",
  "entities": [
    {
      "kind": "person",
      "proposed_slug": "sarah-jones",
      "existing_slug": null,
      "signals": {
        "email": "sarah@acme.com",
        "domain": "acme.com",
        "person_name": "Sarah Jones",
        "job_title": "VP of Sales"
      },
      "aliases": ["Sarah J.", "sjones"],
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "ghost": false
    }
  ],
  "facts": [
    {
      "entity_slug": "sarah-jones",
      "type": "status",
      "triplet": {
        "subject": "sarah-jones",
        "predicate": "role_at",
        "object": "company:acme-corp"
      },
      "text": "Sarah was promoted to VP of Sales at Acme Corp on 2026-04-10.",
      "confidence": 0.92,
      "valid_from": "2026-04-10T00:00:00Z",
      "valid_until": null,
      "source_type": "{{.ArtifactKind}}",
      "source_path": "{{.ArtifactPath}}",
      "sentence_offset": 142,
      "artifact_excerpt": "We're delighted to announce Sarah's promotion to VP of Sales, effective April 10."
    }
  ],
  "notes": "(optional) one sentence on anything you saw but didn't emit and why"
}
```

If the artifact contains nothing extractable, return `{"artifact_sha": "{{.ArtifactSHA}}", "entities": [], "facts": [], "notes": "..."}` with a short reason.

Do not return any text outside the JSON block. The broker parses your output
with a strict JSON parser; any prefix or suffix crashes extraction and routes
this artifact to `wiki/.dlq/extractions.jsonl` for replay.
